               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-142" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-142" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-142" type="surname" value="NORRIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-142" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM NORRIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am bailiff to Mr. Charles Launcelot Hoggatt, the auctioneer.—the prisoner was his carter—I ordered him to go to London on</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184308210013"></xptr>
               <p>the 3rd of August—when he was starting in the morning, I went to the wagon and found a quantity of tares, as many as he ought to have taken in two days—and in a bag concealed under the tares was a bushel of chaff and oats mixed—he had no business to take that—it had come from Mr. Hoggatt's stable—I told him he had done very wrong, it would be a bad job for him—he said "Don't say anything about it to master—for God's sake forgive me for that—I don't care what you say about the tares, if you won't say anything about the chaff and corn"—he had 10 miles to go to London, and was allowed two bundles of tares, but no corn—he bore a very good character.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> It is the first time—I hope you will forgive me.</p>
